{"id": 237148562, "title": "What research actually says about social media and kids\u2019 health", "text": "There is no clear scientific evidence that social media is causing mental health issues among young people. Public health officials are pushing for regulation anyway. U.S. Surgeon General Vivek H. Murthy on Monday called for social media platforms to add warnings reminding parents and kids that the apps might not be safe, citing rising rates of mental health problems among children and teens. It follows an advisory Murthy issued last year about the health threat of loneliness for Americans, in which he named social media as a potential driver of social isolation.", "summary": "Here\u2019s what the research has shown about the effect of social media use on kids\u2019 and teens\u2019 mental health.", "url": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/technology/2024/06/17/social-media-mental-health-research-surgeon-general/", "image": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-apps/imrs.php?src=https://arc-anglerfish-washpost-prod-washpost.s3.amazonaws.com/public/DSFADPMEBHRB6JOQL4YEY7IMVM.jpg&w=1440", "video": null, "publish_date": "2024-06-18 00:44:10", "author": "Tatum Hunter", "authors": ["Tatum Hunter"], "language": "en", "source_country": "us", "sentiment": 0.283}